Text Mining

Hailu Teju

January 6, 2018

Data

The data set for this project is a collection of text documents consisting of news articles, blogs and twits.

Goals

The tasks to be accomplished in this milestone report (towards developing a natural language processing - NLP - application) are:

Exploratory analysis - we perform a thorough exploratory analysis of the data, understand the number of lines and distribution of words in the corpora (the collections of documents).

Understand frequencies of words and word pairs - we build figures and tables to understand variations in the frequencies of words and combinations of words in the data.

Read Files

First we read the three text sources, blog, news, and twitter, and create a list of the three documents.

The full data set
text_source line_count word_count
blog 899288 37334441
news 77259 2643972
twitter 2360148 30373832

Training set

Next, we create a training data set, consisting of about 5% of the original corpora of all the blog, news, and twitter documents, by using the rbinom() function.

Basic summaries of the training set - line counts and word counts

The training set
text_source line_count word_cound
blog 45016 1873247
news 3856 132757
twitter 117907 1518627

From the table above, we see that, for example, the blog sample data set has about 45,000 lines of text and over 1.87 million words.

Preparing Corpora for word analysis

Now, we have created our training set that consists of about 5% of the text in the orginial data set. The next step is to clean up the training set for word analysis:

  • numbers and punctuations will be removed from the corpora.

  • common English words such as a, an, and, is, etc (also known as stopwords) will be removed from the corpora because they are too common in the texts.

  • curse words (compiled locally) will be removed from the corpora.

  • also, hashtags, twitter handles, and unicode characters will be removed from the texts in the corpora.

Next, the Corpora are put into their own Term Document Matrix and ready for further analysis. Words smaller than three characters are omitted.

Most frequent words and n-grams

Exploring the distinct words and their frequencies in the blog, news, and twitter Term Document Matrices, we obtain the following results for the most frequent words in each corpus:

Next step - ngrams and prediction algorithms

The next phase of this data science capstone project is to create a shinny application that predicts what the (most likely) next word is going to be when a user enters a word or phrase. The prediction algorithm is going to use the corpora discussed here and appropriate n-grams to rank the possible next words by frequency in the corpora.

blog <- readLines("en_US.blogs.txt", skipNul = TRUE)
news <- readLines("en_US.news.txt", skipNul = TRUE)
twitter <- readLines("en_US.twitter.txt", skipNul = TRUE)


# Text sources are put into a list and traversed to calculate length and word count
wordCountFunc <- function(myList){sum(str_count(myList, "\\S+"))}

# Data frame to store counts
 df <- data.frame(textSource=c("blog", "news", "twitter"), lineCount=NA, wordCount = NA)


# Put corpora into a list
myList <- list(blog=blog, news=news, twitter=twitter)

# Get line count and word count for each corpus
df$lineCount <- sapply(myList, length)
df$wordCount <- sapply(myList, wordCountFunc)

df  %>% select(text_source=textSource, line_count=lineCount, word_count=wordCount) %>%
        #kable(format = "html", table.attr = "style='width:30%;'") 
        kable(format="html", table.attr="style='color:darkblue;'", caption = "The full data set") %>%
        row_spec(0, background="lightblue") %>%
        kable_styling(full_width=F)

# Create a data frame for samples
sampleDF <- data.frame(textSource=c("blog", "news", "twitter"), lineCount=NA, wordCount=NA)

# Create a list of random variables
set.seed(135)
percent <- 0.05
randoms <- lapply(myList, function(x) rbinom(x, 1, percent))

# Create a new, empty list to store random selections
sampList <- list(blog=NA, news=NA, twitter=NA)

# Use the rbinom() function to traverse the orginal list and select a training set consisting of about 5% of the original data
for (i in 1:length(myList)) {
        sampList[[i]] <- myList[[i]][randoms[[i]]==1]        
}
rm(myList)

# Get counts of sample list
sampleDF$lineCount <- sapply(sampList, length)
sampleDF$wordCount <- sapply(sampList, wordCountFunc)

sampleDF %>% 
        select(text_source = textSource, line_count=lineCount, word_cound=wordCount)  %>% 
        #kable(format = "html", table.attr = "style='width:30%;'") 
        kable(format="html", table.attr="style='color:darkorange;'", caption = "The training set") %>%
        row_spec(0, background="wheat") %>%
        kable_styling(full_width=F)
rm(sampleDF)
# Helper functions 
removeURL <- function(x) gsub("http:[[:alnum:]]*|https:[[:alnum:]]*", "", x)
removeHashTags <- function(x) gsub("#\\S+", "", x)
removeTwitterHandles <- function(x) gsub("@\\S+|[^[:alnum:] ]", "", x)
removeOther <- function(x) gsub("^\\w+[<].+[>][<].+[>]|[<].+[>]([<].+[>])?|[^[:ascii:]]", "", x, perl=T)

# Create corpus class
textCorpus <- VCorpus(VectorSource(sampList))

# Remove twitter handles, hashtags, numbers, punctuations, and other unicode characters
textCorpus <- tm_map(textCorpus, content_transformer(removeOther))
textCorpus <- tm_map(textCorpus, content_transformer(removeURL))
textCorpus <- tm_map(textCorpus, removeNumbers)
textCorpus <- tm_map(textCorpus, removePunctuation)

textCorpus["twitter"] <- tm_map(textCorpus["twitter"], content_transformer(removeHashTags))
textCorpus["twitter"] <- tm_map(textCorpus["twitter"], content_transformer(removeTwitterHandles))
textCorpus["news"] <- tm_map(textCorpus["news"], content_transformer(removeOther))

# Transform all terms to lowercase
textCorpus <- tm_map(textCorpus, content_transformer(tolower))

# Remove curse words and stopwords
textCorpus <- tm_map(textCorpus, removeWords, curseWords)
textCorpus <- tm_map(textCorpus, removeWords, stopwords("english"))

# Single tokenizers
twitterTdm <- TermDocumentMatrix(textCorpus["twitter"], control=list(wordLengths = c(3, Inf)))
newsTdm <- TermDocumentMatrix(textCorpus["news"], control=list(wordLengths = c(3, Inf)))

blogTdm <- TermDocumentMatrix(textCorpus["blog"], control=list(wordLengths = c(3, Inf)))


# Put word count from term-document matrices into data frames
freqBlog <- data.frame(word=blogTdm$dimnames$Terms, frequency = blogTdm$v)
freqNews <- data.frame(word=newsTdm$dimnames$Terms, frequency = newsTdm$v)
freqTwitter <- data.frame(word=twitterTdm$dimnames$Terms, frequency = twitterTdm$v)

# Reorder in descending order of frequency
freqBlog <- arrange(freqBlog, -frequency)
freqNews <- arrange(freqNews, -frequency)
freqTwitter <- arrange(freqTwitter, -frequency)
n <- 25L  # We'll be looking for top 25 words

topBlog <- freqBlog[1:n,]
topNews <- freqNews[1:n,]
topTwitter <- freqTwitter[1:n,]

# Reorder levels so charts plot in order of frequency
topBlog$word <- reorder(topBlog$word, topBlog$frequency)
topNews$word <- reorder(topNews$word, topNews$frequency)
topTwitter$word <- reorder(topTwitter$word, topTwitter$frequency)

BigramTokenizer <- function(x) NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 2, max = 2))
TrigramTokenizer <- function(x) NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 3, max = 3))
FourgramTokenizer <- function(x) NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 4, max = 4))


bigramBlogTdm <- TermDocumentMatrix(textCorpus["blog"], 
                                    control = list(tokenize = BigramTokenizer,
                                                   wordLengths = c(3, Inf)))
freqBigramBlog <- data.frame(bigram = bigramBlogTdm$dimnames$Terms, frequency = bigramBlogTdm$v)
freqBigramBlog <- arrange(freqBigramBlog, -frequency)

bigramNewsTdm <- TermDocumentMatrix(textCorpus["news"], 
                                    control = list(tokenize = BigramTokenizer,
